1
00:00:11,000 --> 00:00:11,820
Good evening.

2
00:00:11,840 --> 00:00:14,005
I trust you had a fruitful day.

3
00:00:14,025 --> 00:00:16,989
I do not say happy, though I hope it has been happy.

4
00:00:17,010 --> 00:00:25,263
Namo dasa bhagavato arahato sama sambudasa.

5
00:00:26,004 --> 00:00:34,357
Namo dasa bhagavato arahato sama sambudasa.

6
00:00:34,927 --> 00:00:42,957
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa.

7
00:00:43,537 --> 00:00:47,703
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

8
00:00:51,185 --> 00:01:04,902
So yesterday we went through the discourse on the seven chariots and we met Mantani Putta, Puna Mantani Putta, and we saw how these two well-advanced

9
00:01:05,201 --> 00:01:13,194
meditators, both of them out of hats, fully self-awakened, greeted each other and recognized each other's greatness.

10
00:01:13,695 --> 00:01:23,031
Mantani put to calling him the closest to the Buddha himself, a great honor to be called that.

11
00:01:24,272 --> 00:01:28,780
And I found out that Kondanya,

12
00:01:29,283 --> 00:01:54,581
uh who was one of the companions of the buddha remember right at the end uh um was actually also a sakyan so they must have known each other as kids although he was he was older than the buddha and uh when he went back home to the sakya country um that's where um that was his sister mantani and his sister

13
00:01:55,168 --> 00:02:23,825
uh had a son who was called who was later called puna so this is a long way around of saying that uh that uh puna mantani was in fact anya kondanya's nephew there's a book on all their names and and the the research has been done most of its commentary um whether it's true or not uh who knows but they're lovely stories

14
00:02:24,768 --> 00:02:31,921
Anyway, so the nitty gritty of these seven purifications, the visuddhi, the seven purifications.

15
00:02:33,525 --> 00:02:39,377
If you want to know them in terms of your practice, the book is Progress of Insight by the Mahasi.

16
00:02:39,396 --> 00:02:41,360
I don't know whether you see that.

17
00:02:42,362 --> 00:02:44,127
No, I thought it would be the wrong way around.

18
00:02:44,768 --> 00:02:46,371
It's called the Progress of Insight.

19
00:02:47,937 --> 00:02:52,584
And in it, of course, there are what we call the jnanas, the past jnanas.

20
00:02:52,844 --> 00:02:56,371
So we'll come to that with a warning.

21
00:02:57,391 --> 00:03:00,556
So the first one is the purification of virtue.

22
00:03:00,616 --> 00:03:06,447
This is really, you know, getting your moral act right.

23
00:03:07,649 --> 00:03:13,437
In terms of all of your daily life, you know, we want to stop killing people, thieving and stuff like that.

24
00:03:13,942 --> 00:03:24,614
But in terms of meditation practice, when you come on retreat, you know, if there's something that's happened which you need to clear your heart of, you know, it's always best to do it.

25
00:03:25,014 --> 00:03:31,801
You know, you've had angry words with somebody, and if you come on retreat with that, it tends to be a bit obsessive, you know.

26
00:03:32,802 --> 00:03:36,606
So it's always good to come with a sort of clear conscience to a retreat.

27
00:03:37,247 --> 00:03:39,530
And that's one of your first purifications.

28
00:03:40,891 --> 00:03:43,914
But the problem is that...

29
00:03:44,705 --> 00:03:48,128
The purification of, well, just a minute.

30
00:03:48,849 --> 00:03:52,876
The next one is the purification of the mind, which is dealing with the hindrances.

31
00:03:53,637 --> 00:04:05,731
So, of course, we do that in the meditation, all the desires, the hatreds, the dullness and lethargies, all the restlessness and the shames and guilts.

32
00:04:05,812 --> 00:04:07,373
And then finally, of course, doubt.

33
00:04:08,415 --> 00:04:12,501
So those, of course, we're dealing with during our practice.

34
00:04:12,751 --> 00:04:38,201
but also in daily life remember you know when desires come up if you're right there with it you can always you know hold on and say is this is this skillful or not just wait for that energy to disappear so these visuddhis these purifications are not only applicable to the actual practice of vipassana on a retreat they're also applicable just in ordinary daily life

35
00:04:39,396 --> 00:05:03,665
um now sometimes people get into a sort of um a dilemma because you can't attain full liberation until you're perfectly purified on the other hand you can't be perfectly purified until you've attained uh until you've attained nibbana now nibbana here is the final point when you become an arahat

36
00:05:04,185 --> 00:05:10,391
And unfortunately, especially in the order, you can get very, very tight about this.

37
00:05:11,572 --> 00:05:15,476
I have a rather sad story of somebody I knew whom I got to know rather well.

38
00:05:16,237 --> 00:05:23,045
We were meditating together for some time and he wasn't getting anywhere in his practice.

39
00:05:23,064 --> 00:05:33,314
So he presumed that it was because his sila, his morality and the rule keeping wasn't being kept well enough, perfectly.

40
00:05:34,915 --> 00:05:39,641
So he left and began to read the Vinaya, all the little rules and everything, you know.

41
00:05:40,161 --> 00:05:48,232
And he came across the original size of this upper robe that you see hanging behind the Buddha here, right?

42
00:05:49,112 --> 00:05:57,403
Now, actually, the original size was basically just a cloth that you put over the top part of your body when you entered into a village.

43
00:05:57,483 --> 00:06:00,146
It was just a modest thing to do.

44
00:06:00,413 --> 00:06:06,089
And in time, of course, it grew to be this long robe, you see.

45
00:06:06,973 --> 00:06:11,487
And also the bowl, you know, the monk's bowl is rather big, you know.

46
00:06:12,209 --> 00:06:18,117
When you go on alms round and it's full, there's no way you can eat what they put in that bowl.

47
00:06:18,958 --> 00:06:31,855
But the reason it got so big was because it became the vessel that you carried your little bits and bobs in when you went wandering from village to village or from monastery to monastery.

48
00:06:32,475 --> 00:06:43,535
So when he read these rules, he went off to see Ananda Maitreya, Venerable Ananda Maitreya, who was a very, very famous monk in Sri Lanka.

49
00:06:44,216 --> 00:06:52,331
He'll come up again when I talk about the insight knowledges, who was understood to be quite a scholar.

50
00:06:53,012 --> 00:06:56,458
And he agreed that these weren't strictly Vinaya.

51
00:06:57,434 --> 00:06:59,418
We went to a Katina ceremony.

52
00:06:59,658 --> 00:07:14,615
That's the ceremony at the end of the rainy season, October, November, October, when there's a big party and lay people bring to the monastery those things that monks and nuns might need.

53
00:07:15,202 --> 00:07:20,067
the monastics might need, umbrellas, soap, toothpaste, stuff like that.

54
00:07:20,809 --> 00:07:27,375
And he came with this little thing on his shoulder, and he also had convinced a younger monk to follow him.

55
00:07:27,776 --> 00:07:38,168
And instead of a bowl, because the bowl originally was to be the depth of your hand, of your palm here, you see, that was supposed to be the depth of the bowl.

56
00:07:38,749 --> 00:07:44,214
And so he turned up with this natty little cover over his shoulders and a biscuit tin, you see.

57
00:07:46,927 --> 00:07:50,052
And when the monk saw this, they just said he's gone mad.

58
00:07:51,014 --> 00:07:54,658
When you slightly go off like that, they just say you've gone mad.

59
00:07:55,120 --> 00:07:59,225
And that means that they look upon you with a certain pity, right?

60
00:07:59,326 --> 00:08:03,793
They not sort of jump on you and say, hey, what about this rule and how dare you do that?

61
00:08:04,112 --> 00:08:05,915
They just sort of say he's gone a bit mad.

62
00:08:06,401 --> 00:08:19,178
Anyway, seemingly he drove himself into this sort of dead end corner where he's absolutely obsessive about keeping every little rule so that he can move spiritually.

63
00:08:19,920 --> 00:08:29,612
And what I heard later was that he left and he went to Thailand and they basically stopped him, asked him to leave the monastery.

64
00:08:29,872 --> 00:08:32,375
And he left eventually and went back home.

65
00:08:32,355 --> 00:08:34,418
So a bit of a sad story there.

66
00:08:34,479 --> 00:08:37,023
So don't get obsessive about purity.

67
00:08:37,563 --> 00:08:40,589
We just work with it as it comes, just as it comes.

68
00:08:43,673 --> 00:08:47,038
So that's the purity of the mind.

69
00:08:47,158 --> 00:08:51,745
OK, so we've been through the purity of our basic morality, purity of the mind.

70
00:08:52,265 --> 00:08:54,649
And then we come to the purity of view.

71
00:08:55,211 --> 00:08:59,157
And that really do with over time.

72
00:08:59,423 --> 00:09:11,518
all this business about self, which we've been through before, it's beginning to understand what the difference between the body and the mind, looking at it more closely.

73
00:09:12,578 --> 00:09:15,241
Let me see now, I've got an example here.

74
00:09:15,802 --> 00:09:18,225
It's basically looking at the five aggregates.

75
00:09:18,706 --> 00:09:24,352
So we've been through that, if you remember, just to recognize that this is a compendium, right?

76
00:09:24,373 --> 00:09:26,916
It feels like one being, it feels like me.

77
00:09:27,722 --> 00:09:33,530
But actually, you know, the body has its own little life form, all these billions of cells or whatever.

78
00:09:34,292 --> 00:09:44,025
And then we've got this whole feeling thing that's going on inside the body, which is both from the heart, the emotional stuff, and from the body, feelings, sensations.

79
00:09:44,606 --> 00:09:53,700
We've got all the stuff about how we build up memory with images and conceptual images and abstract thinking.

80
00:09:54,341 --> 00:09:57,325
And then we have all our habits and the way we think.

81
00:09:57,710 --> 00:10:06,080
which we've taken a lot from our culture, and some of it, of course, has been our own ingenuity, creating our own little special habits.

82
00:10:06,880 --> 00:10:09,264
And all of that appears on consciousness.

83
00:10:10,125 --> 00:10:12,668
The consciousness is like a screen upon which things appear.

84
00:10:14,629 --> 00:10:25,381
So it's beginning to separate all that and beginning to get the feel of this not being a person, an entity, whole, entire unto itself.

85
00:10:25,462 --> 00:10:26,703
It's made up of pieces.

86
00:10:27,240 --> 00:10:32,727
So that's this beginning to understand the purification of view.

87
00:10:34,188 --> 00:10:41,337
When it comes to the purification of overcoming doubt, that's to do with conditionality.

88
00:10:42,438 --> 00:10:50,227
And this brings us to things like dependent origination and seeing that everything is conditioned.

89
00:10:50,729 --> 00:10:51,970
We do have a choice.

90
00:10:52,770 --> 00:10:55,914
We know that when especially around desires.

91
00:10:56,602 --> 00:11:02,432
If we see a desire which is unwholesome, we can hold it there and let it pass.

92
00:11:02,952 --> 00:11:05,998
But even that is conditioned by our wisdom.

93
00:11:06,639 --> 00:11:08,001
So everything is conditioned.

94
00:11:08,062 --> 00:11:10,365
Everything has a cause, okay?

95
00:11:11,187 --> 00:11:12,649
And that's beginning to understand that.

96
00:11:12,990 --> 00:11:18,678
Now, this whole idea of cause and effect is quite profound.

97
00:11:19,801 --> 00:11:21,143
It's understood that

98
00:11:21,510 --> 00:11:46,977
uh when a person uh really grasps conditionality uh that they that they're actually on the path and in the commentaries they're called a chula sotapanna which means a lesser sotapanna a lesser stream entrant that's how important uh understanding conditionality is everything is dependent on something else nothing arises of its

99
00:11:47,227 --> 00:11:48,870
of its own accord.

100
00:11:50,392 --> 00:12:01,107
And so we're always looking at the immediacy of those components that bring something about and what's happened in the past to bring something about.

101
00:12:03,070 --> 00:12:05,653
Perhaps we'll come to that at a later stage.

102
00:12:06,434 --> 00:12:07,437
Conditionality.

103
00:12:07,797 --> 00:12:11,903
And its main expression is through dependence origination.

104
00:12:12,894 --> 00:12:31,376
So that's why we're always looking at this distinction, especially this little trilogy of contact, sorry, of Vedana, which is the feeling, the feeling tone of what we're experiencing, pleasant, unpleasant.

105
00:12:32,486 --> 00:12:48,833
how we're reacting to it and then that sudden grasping and to stay steadily between the original feeling, the original pleasant, unpleasant state and that reaction and waiting for the reaction to go.

106
00:12:49,554 --> 00:12:56,807
And that gives us that clarity, that wisdom to then act in a way that's going to be a benefit to us.

107
00:13:00,735 --> 00:13:04,042
And then the next one is knowing what is the path and what is not the path.

108
00:13:04,923 --> 00:13:17,006
This on a worldly, on a very obvious level, we begin to realize that all the sensual pleasures really have to be let go off as places where we're going to seek

109
00:13:16,986 --> 00:13:43,095
our liberation they're all right when they come as uh as uh what's his name blake said in that lovely poem uh to kiss a joy as it flies is to live in eternity's sunrise but as soon as you grasp it as soon as you try and hold on to it misery misery awaits you so um it's this business of recognizing that now in our practice when we actually come to practice

110
00:13:43,413 --> 00:13:49,841
Often in our sittings we'll get these beautiful states, you see, and then we'll think, oh, well, that's it.

111
00:13:50,001 --> 00:13:51,123
That must be it, you see.

112
00:13:52,063 --> 00:13:54,067
And, of course, it isn't.

113
00:13:54,086 --> 00:14:01,596
And this comes about, there are various ways in which these beautiful states arise.

114
00:14:02,418 --> 00:14:06,903
There are ten of them, actually, nine of which are fine.

115
00:14:07,344 --> 00:14:09,706
It's the last one, the holding on to something.

116
00:14:09,956 --> 00:14:13,381
which makes them into kilesa, defilements.

117
00:14:14,322 --> 00:14:18,789
So the first one is that people have insight.

118
00:14:18,830 --> 00:14:19,792
It's quite remarkable.

119
00:14:19,812 --> 00:14:25,921
Some people in their practice suddenly see something and they almost go out and write a book about it.

120
00:14:26,260 --> 00:14:28,605
They've just had that clarity of understanding.

121
00:14:29,525 --> 00:14:37,618
And they think that therefore they must have had a really deep insight.

122
00:14:37,884 --> 00:14:43,871
I remember one monk I met who was really very clear about the Dharma.

123
00:14:44,172 --> 00:14:50,119
He was absolutely certain that he was born as a stream entrant, that he had it in his past life.

124
00:14:50,480 --> 00:14:53,062
But else, how could he explain the Dharma so clearly?

125
00:14:53,143 --> 00:14:55,264
How could he speak about it so clearly?

126
00:14:55,765 --> 00:14:57,148
And that's a confusion, that is.

127
00:14:57,548 --> 00:15:00,091
The intellect is very clever at confusing you.

128
00:15:00,491 --> 00:15:05,918
Remember the story of Lucifer, who thought he was equal to God in intellect, eh?

129
00:15:06,320 --> 00:15:09,082
He found himself in hell, so be careful.

130
00:15:09,143 --> 00:15:20,154
Then sometimes people get beautiful light, like they're suddenly surrounded, like an inner light which is overwhelming sometimes.

131
00:15:20,634 --> 00:15:25,500
And that, again, is just a product of good concentration.

132
00:15:26,201 --> 00:15:28,583
And some people might think, oh, well, that's it, you see.

133
00:15:31,047 --> 00:15:34,149
I know somebody who actually felt that.

134
00:15:34,871 --> 00:15:47,993
There's also a knowledge, much the same as insight, that they suddenly understand things at a more intellectual level, and that also can be a bit of a trap.

135
00:15:48,894 --> 00:15:59,630
Then you can feel extraordinarily happy, extraordinarily joyous, and you think to yourself, this is so pure a joy, this is what Nirvana is.

136
00:15:59,932 --> 00:16:03,197
And then you have to remind yourself that there's no mental states in Nirvana.

137
00:16:03,216 --> 00:16:05,038
There are no emotions in Nirvana.

138
00:16:05,841 --> 00:16:14,974
And when Sariputta is asked, you see, how is it you talk about the bliss of Nirvana when there's no emotions there?

139
00:16:14,994 --> 00:16:18,918
He said, well, it's the very absence of emotions, which is the bliss of Nirvana.

140
00:16:18,938 --> 00:16:21,383
Well, that's very confusing for us, isn't it?

141
00:16:23,876 --> 00:16:32,004
And then you can have this wonderful sense of peace, this sort of real deep peace where, oh, you know, like this, this must be Nirvana.

142
00:16:33,865 --> 00:16:47,577
And then there's happiness, which is more of a, the rapture, the rapture is felt more as a sort of a physical thing, a physical ecstasy, you know, whereas the happiness is more of a mental ecstasy.

143
00:16:47,597 --> 00:16:53,243
And then suddenly you get this huge determination, which,

144
00:16:53,559 --> 00:17:03,668
is over-determination actually, and it can cause you to try and get nibbana, and that can also be a bit fatal.

145
00:17:05,374 --> 00:17:08,682
A load of energy can come up, it's quite remarkable, you can sit for

146
00:17:10,115 --> 00:17:12,257
But you can go through a whole night without any sleep.

147
00:17:12,857 --> 00:17:14,338
I know somebody went through two nights.

148
00:17:14,819 --> 00:17:23,328
Just a pure energy comes up where you can just maintain that mindfulness just continuously, you know, over and over.

149
00:17:23,648 --> 00:17:27,894
And, of course, such a person might think, well, this is it, I've made it.

150
00:17:27,953 --> 00:17:35,521
Also awareness, the awareness can be very bright and very sharp, especially for somebody who hasn't done very much practice.

151
00:17:35,582 --> 00:17:39,665
Suddenly to have this really sharp awareness, they think, well, that's it, see?

152
00:17:40,928 --> 00:17:49,036
And the delight at the end really is hanging on to these things as meaning, as being some sort of real spiritual practice.

153
00:17:49,096 --> 00:17:54,301
But actually, they're all expressions of the pure heart and concentration.

154
00:17:55,942 --> 00:17:58,046
So then you have to let go of that, you see.

155
00:17:58,125 --> 00:17:59,867
So you know, well, that's not the path.

156
00:17:59,988 --> 00:18:02,210
You see, that's not the path.

157
00:18:02,230 --> 00:18:04,632
And so one returns to the meditation.

158
00:18:04,732 --> 00:18:10,057
One returns to just observing, just feeling, just experiencing.

159
00:18:10,730 --> 00:18:18,080
And during that time, again, these three characteristics become more and more obvious to a person.

160
00:18:18,520 --> 00:18:22,606
So they might be more obvious of desire at certain times.

161
00:18:22,646 --> 00:18:25,191
They might be more obvious of impermanence.

162
00:18:25,211 --> 00:18:31,559
They might recognize that things are happening of their own accord, that they're not always under our control.

163
00:18:32,080 --> 00:18:37,327
And this is not only in the meditation room, it's also in ordinary daily life.

164
00:18:37,662 --> 00:18:50,642
You might ask yourself, for instance, if you drive a car and you've driven between point A and point B or you've actually arrived and you can't remember yourself driving because you might have been somewhere else.

165
00:18:50,662 --> 00:18:53,224
Well, who's been driving, for heaven's sake?

166
00:18:54,907 --> 00:18:58,252
So if that isn't an experience of not self, I don't know what is.

167
00:18:59,633 --> 00:19:08,185
And then you might come in and you've opened the door and you put the keys down and you can't remember where you put the key.

168
00:19:08,205 --> 00:19:09,067
But something happened.

169
00:19:09,106 --> 00:19:09,948
You did put the key.

170
00:19:10,008 --> 00:19:11,891
There was a putting of the keys down.

171
00:19:11,951 --> 00:19:15,375
And that was done by whom?

172
00:19:16,258 --> 00:19:22,586
So it's little things like that that awaken you to the fact that this self isn't entirely in control.

173
00:19:25,907 --> 00:19:35,318
And then finally, there's the first what you might call true insight, which is the knowledge of rise and fall.

174
00:19:35,980 --> 00:19:38,702
A person sees that now much more clearly on the breath.

175
00:19:39,103 --> 00:19:44,148
And this, again, this doesn't need to happen while you're sitting.

176
00:19:44,569 --> 00:19:48,493
It can happen while you're riding on a bus, while you're walking down the street.

177
00:19:48,594 --> 00:19:54,260
This awareness, this intuitive awareness can grasp these things at any time.

178
00:19:55,000 --> 00:20:01,946
And then the next one after that, after there's a clearer viewing of that, is dissolution.

179
00:20:02,788 --> 00:20:16,642
Now, this point of dissolution is just when there's a real grasping, a real direct insight, you actually experience, there's an experience of things actually vanishing.

180
00:20:17,884 --> 00:20:24,130
Now, that has a big effect on us because, normally speaking, we're much more aware of when things begin.

181
00:20:24,598 --> 00:20:31,252
So you'll notice that as soon as you finish one piece of chocolate, before you've actually swallowed it, you're on to the next one.

182
00:20:31,594 --> 00:20:35,020
So we're always one step ahead of ourselves.

183
00:20:35,060 --> 00:20:41,493
We're always into something new, something exciting, something drawing us always into the future.

184
00:20:41,845 --> 00:20:48,336
But this is actually a sudden realization that everything actually does disappear.

185
00:20:48,375 --> 00:20:49,617
Everything does collapse.

186
00:20:49,699 --> 00:20:50,980
Everything does vanish.

187
00:20:52,063 --> 00:20:54,086
And that has an effect on us.

188
00:20:55,347 --> 00:20:59,756
It's like coming to terms with death in a way.

189
00:20:59,955 --> 00:21:06,688
It's an opening that recognizes that, you know, things end kaput and all that.

190
00:21:07,343 --> 00:21:36,726
and so what happens then is uh some fear comes up um and during the next period which are known as the the suffering nyanas or the dukkha nyanas uh also it can be mixed up with your own psychology so there's this underlying awakening of your spirit of of spiritual insight into the way things really are but it also can bring up stuff from your uh a more surface level psychology

191
00:21:36,992 --> 00:21:39,916
So there's fear comes up, which is a shock.

192
00:21:39,997 --> 00:21:40,577
It's a shock.

193
00:21:42,400 --> 00:21:52,074
And then after that, there's, there's a sort of downer, uh, where you might feel depressed and that all these things can last any length of time, any length of time.

194
00:21:52,473 --> 00:21:57,300
It's not, it's not a case of zipping through it in a few days or something.

195
00:21:58,201 --> 00:22:01,666
Uh, I know people who've taken years to go through these stages.

196
